{:correct? true, :passed 7, :total-tests 7, :q-num 1, :trace [{:iteration 0, :response nil, :thinking "Let me think about this problem. I need to generate an increasing lazy sequence of palindromic numbers >= n.\n\nThe naive approach would be to filter all numbers >= n for palindrome property, but that's too slow.\n\nA smarter approach: generate palindromes by length, in increasing order. For a given digit count d, I can generate all palindromes of that length, then move to d+1.\n\nFor d digits:\n- If d is odd: take a (d+1)/2 digit prefix, mirror the first (d-1)/2 digits\n- If d is even: take a d/2 digit prefix, mirror all d/2 digits\n\nBut I need to be careful about leading zeros in the prefix.\n\nLet me think about this differently. I'll generate palindromes by \"half-length\":\n- For half-length 1: 0-9 → palindromes 0-9 (1-digit)\n- For half-length 1, even: 0-9 → palindromes 00, 11, 22, ..., 99 (2-digit). But wait, 00 = 0 which we already have. Actually for 2-digit palindromes, the prefix ranges from 10-99 giving 1001, 1111, ..., 9999. No wait, that's 4 digits.\n\nLet me reconsider. Let me think in terms of the number of digits.\n\nFor 1-digit palindromes: 0, 1, 2, ..., 9\nFor 2-digit palindromes: 11, 22, ..., 99 (prefix 1-9, mirrored)\nFor 3-digit palindromes: 101, 111, ..., 191, 202, ..., 999 (prefix 10-99, middle digit 0-9, mirror first 2 digits → first 1 digit reversed)\n  Actually: for odd d=3, take prefix of length 2 (10-99), reverse first 1 digit → e.g., 10 → 101, 11 → 111, ..., 99 → 999\nFor 4-digit palindromes: 1001, 1111, ..., 9999 (prefix 10-99, mirror both digits → 10 → 1001, 11 → 1111)\nFor 5-digit palindromes: 10001, 10101, ..., 99999 (prefix 100-999, mirror first 2 digits)\n\nSo the pattern:\n- For d-digit palindromes:\n  - half = ceil(d/2)\n  - prefix range: if d == 1, then 0-9; else 10^(half-1) to 10^half - 1\n  - odd d: take prefix p, append (p / 10) reversed (drop last digit of prefix, reverse)\n  - even d: take prefix p, append p reversed\n\nLet me write this:\n\n```clojure\n(defn make-palindrome [prefix odd?]\n  (if odd?\n    (let [s (str prefix)\n          dropped (subs s 0 (dec (count s)))]\n      (Long/parseLong (str s (apply str (reverse dropped)))))\n    (let [s (str prefix)]\n      (Long/parseLong (str s (apply str (reverse s)))))))\n```\n\nThen for each digit length d from 1 upward, generate all palindromes and filter >= n.\n\nBut I need this to be lazy and efficient. Let me generate by digit length.\n\n```clojure\n(defn palindromes-of-length [d]\n  (let [half (int (Math/ceil (/ d 2)))\n        odd? (odd? d)\n        lo (if (= d 1) 0 (int (Math/pow 10 (dec half))))\n        hi (dec (int (Math/pow 10 half)))]\n    (map #(make-palindrome % odd?) (range lo (inc hi)))))\n```\n\nThen:\n```clojure\n(defn palindromes [n]\n  (let [start-d (if (zero? n) 1 (count (str n)))]\n    (->> (iterate inc start-d)\n         (mapcat palindromes-of-length)\n         (filter #(>= % n)))))\n```\n\nWait, but for n=0, we need 0 which is 1 digit. For n=162, we need palindromes starting from 171 which is 3 digits. The start digit count should be the number of digits in n, but we might also need to check d-1 if n itself is at the boundary... actually no, since we filter >= n, starting from the digit count of n is fine. If n=100 (3 digits), palindromes of length 3 starting from 101 would be correct.\n\nActually wait, what about n=0? count of \"0\" is 1. Palindromes of length 1: 0,1,...,9. Filtering >= 0 gives 0,1,...,9. Then length 2: 11,...,99. That's correct.\n\nWhat about n=10? count of \"10\" is 2. Palindromes of length 2: 11,22,...,99. Filtering >= 10 gives 11,22,...,99. But what about palindromes of length 1? None of those are >= 10. So starting from digit count 2 is fine.\n\nHmm but what if n=9? count is 1. Palindromes of length 1 >= 9: 9. Then length 2: 11,... Correct.\n\nWhat if n=10? count is 2. Length 2 palindromes >= 10: 11,... But we miss nothing from length 1 since all are < 10. Good.\n\nNow, the issue with the