igit palindromes. 6666 palindromes from 7-digit range (9000 total) is fine.\n\nAnd the set test: `(set (take 199 (__ 0))) = (set (map #(first (__ %)) (range 0 10000)))` - this verifies that for each starting point 0-9999, the first palindrome >= that point is in the first 199 palindromes starting from 0. This should work since the first 199 palindromes from 0 cover up to some point in the 3-digit range.\n\nLet me count: 10 (1-digit) + 9 (2-digit) + 90 (3-digit) = 109 palindromes up through 3 digits. We need 199 total, so 90 more from 4-digit: 1001, 1111, ..., up to 19191. Actually 199 - 109 = 90, which is exactly all 4-digit palindromes. So the first 199 palindromes go up to 9999. Any starting point 0-9999 will have its first palindrome in this set. Good.\n\nNow let me code this properly. I need to be careful with the function form since `__` is textually replaced.\n\n```clojure\n(fn [n]\n  (let [make-pal (fn [prefix odd?]\n                   (let [s (str prefix)]\n                     (if odd?\n                       (Long/parseLong (str s (apply str (reverse (subs s 0 (dec (count s)))))))\n                       (Long/parseLong (str s (apply str (reverse s)))))))\n        pals-of-len (fn [d]\n                      (let [half (quot (+ d 1) 2)\n                            odd? (odd? d)\n                            lo (if (= d 1) 0 (long (Math/pow 10 (dec half))))\n                            hi (long (Math/pow 10 half))]\n                        (map #(make-pal % odd?) (range lo hi)))\n        start-d (if (zero? n) 1 (count (str n)))]\n    (filter #(>= % n) (mapcat pals-of-len (iterate inc start-d)))))\n```\n\nWait, I should be careful: `(long (Math/pow 10 0))` = 1. For d=1, half=1, lo would be 1 but I override to 0. For d=2, half=1, lo = 10^0 = 1, hi = 10^1 = 10. Range 1-9 → palindromes 11, 22, ..., 99. Correct.\n\nFor d=3, half=2, lo=10, hi=100. Range 10-99 → 90 prefixes → 90 palindromes. Correct.\n\nFor d=10, half=5, lo=10000, hi=100000. Range 10000-99999 → 90000