9 (14 digits)? pow10(6) = 1000000 for half=7. That's fine for Long.\n\nActually wait, I should think about whether Long/parseLong can handle numbers up to 18 digits. Yes, Long/MAX_VALUE is about 9.2 × 10^18, so up to 18 digits. The tests don't seem to go beyond 10-11 digits, so we're fine.\n\nLet me also think about the `str` and `reverse` approach. For each palindrome, we're converting to string, doing string ops, then parsing back. This might be slower than arithmetic, but since we're generating palindromes directly (not filtering), the total work is much less than the naive approach.\n\nAn alternative arithmetic approach:\n```clojure\n(defn make-pal-arith [prefix odd?]\n  (let [rev (fn [x] (loop [n x r 0] (if (zero? n) r (recur (quot n 10) (+ (* r 10) (rem n 10)))))]\n    (if odd?\n      (+ (* prefix (pow10 (dec (quot (+ d 1) 2)))) (rev (quot prefix 10)))\n      (+ (* prefix (pow10 (quot (+ d 1) 2))) (rev prefix)))))\n```\n\nThis is more complex but avoids string conversion. For the SCI environment, string operations might actually be faster since they're JVM primitives. Let me stick with the string approach.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the performance. The test `(nth (__ 0) 10101)` needs to lazily generate and skip palindromes. With `filter` + `mapcat`, each step involves:\n1. Getting next from mapcat (which gets next from current pals-of-len, or moves to next length)\n2. Checking if >= n\n3. If not, discarding and continuing\n\nFor the nth operation, this is O(10101) steps, each involving string operations. Should be fast enough.\n\nThe test `(apply < (take 6666 (__ 9999999)))` needs 6666 palindromes, each from 7-digit range (prefix 4-digit). String ops on 7-8 chars. Fast.\n\nThe test `(= (set (take 199 (__ 0))) (set (map #(first (__ %)) (range 0 10000))))` is the most concerning. It creates 10000 lazy sequences, each calling first. Each `first` needs to generate palindromes from some starting point. The starting points range from 0 to 9999, so digit lengths